            <div class="tips-title">Sleep Quality Tips</div>
            <div class="tips-grid">
                <div class="tip-item">
                    <h3>Keep a consistent schedule</h3>
                    <p>Go to bed and wake up at the same time every day — even on weekends. This reinforces your circadian rhythm.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-item">
                    <h3>Limit blue light before bed</h3>
                    <p>Screens suppress melatonin production. Stop using phones, tablets, and computers at least 30–60 minutes before sleep.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-item">
                    <h3>Cool your bedroom</h3>
                    <p>The ideal sleeping temperature is 60–67°F (15–19°C). A cooler room triggers your body's natural sleep signals.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-item">
                    <h3>Avoid caffeine after 2 PM</h3>
                    <p>Caffeine has a half-life of 5–6 hours. An afternoon coffee can still affect your ability to fall asleep at night.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-item">
                    <h3>Exercise — but not too late</h3>
                    <p>Regular exercise improves sleep quality, but intense workouts within 2–3 hours of bedtime can keep you alert.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="tip-item">
                    <h3>Wind down with a routine</h3>
                    <p>Reading, stretching, or a warm shower signals your body it's time to sleep. Consistency matters more than the activity.</p>
                </div>
