        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <div class="seo-content">
            <h2>How the Sleep Cycle Calculator Works</h2>
            <p>This sleep calculator helps you figure out the best time to go to sleep or wake up by aligning with your natural <strong>90-minute sleep cycles</strong>. Instead of aiming for a specific number of hours, you aim to complete full cycles — which means you wake up at the end of a lighter sleep stage rather than being pulled out of deep sleep.</p>

            <h3>Why 90-minute cycles matter</h3>
            <p>Each sleep cycle lasts roughly 90 minutes and moves through four stages: two stages of light sleep (N1 and N2), one stage of deep sleep (N3), and REM (rapid eye movement) sleep. Waking during deep sleep causes <strong>sleep inertia</strong> — that heavy, groggy feeling that can last 30 minutes or more. By timing your alarm to coincide with the end of a cycle, you wake during lighter sleep and feel significantly more alert.</p>

            <h3>The 14-minute fall-asleep buffer</h3>
            <p>This calculator adds 14 minutes to your bedtime calculations. Research shows the average healthy adult takes about 14 minutes to fall asleep (called <strong>sleep onset latency</strong>). This means if you need to start your first sleep cycle at 11:00 PM, the calculator recommends getting into bed at 10:46 PM.</p>

            <h3>How many sleep cycles do you need?</h3>
            <p>Most adults function best on 5 or 6 complete cycles per night:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>4 cycles (6 hours):</strong> The minimum for short-term function. Adequate for occasional use but not sustainable.</li>
                <li><strong>5 cycles (7.5 hours):</strong> Meets the lower end of recommended sleep for most adults. A good target for most people.</li>
                <li><strong>6 cycles (9 hours):</strong> Ideal for recovery, teens, athletes, or anyone feeling sleep-deprived.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>What time should I go to sleep?</h3>
            <p>The best bedtime depends on when you need to wake up. For a 6:00 AM alarm, ideal bedtimes are 8:46 PM (6 cycles), 10:16 PM (5 cycles), or 11:46 PM (4 cycles). For a 7:00 AM alarm, try 9:46 PM, 11:16 PM, or 12:46 AM. The calculator above does this math for any target time.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <div class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What time should I go to sleep if I want to wake up at 6am?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">To wake up at 6:00 AM feeling refreshed, you should go to sleep at 8:46 PM (5 cycles, 7.5 hours), 10:16 PM (4 cycles, 6 hours), or 11:46 PM (3 cycles, 4.5 hours). These times account for the average 14 minutes it takes to fall asleep and align with the end of a complete 90-minute sleep cycle.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long is one sleep cycle?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">One complete sleep cycle lasts approximately 90 minutes and consists of four stages: light sleep (N1), deeper sleep (N2), deep sleep (N3/slow-wave sleep), and REM sleep. Most adults complete 4 to 6 cycles per night.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why do I feel tired after 8 hours of sleep?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Feeling tired after 8 hours likely means your alarm woke you in the middle of a sleep cycle, particularly during deep sleep or REM. Eight hours doesn't align perfectly with 90-minute cycles. Try sleeping 7.5 hours (5 cycles) or 9 hours (6 cycles) instead.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How long does it take to fall asleep?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The average person takes about 14 minutes to fall asleep, known as sleep onset latency. If you regularly take more than 20–30 minutes, you may have sleep onset insomnia. If you fall asleep in under 5 minutes, it could indicate sleep deprivation.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Is it better to get 6 hours of sleep or 7.5 hours?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">7.5 hours (5 complete sleep cycles) is generally better than 6 hours (4 cycles) for most adults. The National Sleep Foundation recommends 7–9 hours for adults aged 18–64. However, 6 hours aligned with complete cycles is better than 7 hours that interrupts a cycle mid-way.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What happens during deep sleep?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Deep sleep (N3 or slow-wave sleep) is when your body repairs tissues, builds bone and muscle, and strengthens the immune system. Growth hormone is released during this stage. It typically occurs more in the first half of the night and makes up about 15–20% of total sleep time in adults.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How many hours of sleep do I need by age?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Newborns (0–3 months) need 14–17 hours, infants (4–11 months) 12–15 hours, toddlers (1–2 years) 11–14 hours, preschoolers (3–5 years) 10–13 hours, school-age (6–13 years) 9–11 hours, teenagers (14–17 years) 8–10 hours, young adults and adults (18–64 years) 7–9 hours, and older adults (65+) 7–8 hours.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Should I use a sleep calculator every night?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Using a sleep calculator helps establish a consistent sleep schedule. Once you find times that work well for you, try to maintain those bedtimes and wake times every day — including weekends. Consistency reinforces your circadian rhythm and improves overall sleep quality more than any single night of perfect timing.</div>
            </div>
